  "prompt": "College and NCAA Football: (NFL) In overtime, is the kicking team allowed to do an onside kick and if successful does the other team get the ball afterwards?",
  "response": "In the NFL, starting with the 2022 season, the overtime rules for the playoffs and regular season are as follows:\n\nIf the team that receives the ball first scores a touchdown on their opening possession, they win the game. However, if they only score a field goal, the other team gets a possession and can win with a touchdown or tie with a field goal.\n\nIf the first team does not score or turns the ball over, the other team can win with a touchdown, or the game can end in a tie if neither team scores.\n\nRegarding an onside kick:\n- An onside kick is allowed in overtime\n- If the kicking team successfully recovers the onside kick, they gain possession\n- There are no special restrictions on onside kicks in overtime compared to regulation time\n\nSo if the kicking team successfully recovers an onside kick, they would indeed get the ball and continue their offensive drive.",
